<br>
Maclean's Magazine - Sept 24/2001<br>
<br>
&quot;THE SPIDER AT THE CENTRE OF A DEADLY WEB&quot;<br>
His bearded face flickered across television screens mere hours after the attack, his name repeated as the single most likely suspect responsible for so much death and destruction.  Even prior to Sept. 11, 2001, Osama bin Laden - a 44-year-old Saudi-born multi-millionaire and international terrorist - was America's most wanted man.  Today, he is the world's.  Although in Western eyes his name is synonymous with evil, he possesses near-mythical status among disaffected Muslim activists as the sharpest thorn in the side of the United States.<br>
<br>
Born in Riyadh, Saudi Arabia, in 1957 to a father who would become one of that country's largest and most influential construction magnates, bin Laden lived an early life of privilege.  But in 1979, when the Soviet Union invaded Afghanistan, he left Saudi Arabia and used his considerable wealth and connections to help arm and aid the country's mujahedeen guerrillas fighting the Soviets.  For a decade, with every shipment of medicine, troops and guns he brought into the war effort, his influence and stature grew.  The Afghani rebels were also backed by the United States, which funnelled $3 billion into the conflict and trained mujahadeen fighters.  According to some reports, the CIA may also have helped train bin Laden and his fighters in terror techniques.  But bin Laden did not look upon the United States as Afghanistan's - or Islam's - protector.<br>
<br>
After the Soviets withdrew from Afghanistan in 1989, bin Laden returned to Saudi Arabia a hero, and became an outspoken opponent of the royal family's rule.  He fled the kingdom for Sudan in 1991 in the wake of the Persian Gulf War, considering the U.S. military presence in Saudi Arabia - home to Islam's two holiest sites, Mecca and Medina - an affront to his religion.  Since then, bin Laden has openly advocated the removal of U.S. troops from Saudi Arabia - and the destruction of Israel - and has issued calls to Muslims to &quot;kill Americans and the Jews.&quot;  In 1994, Saudi Arabia withdrew bin Laden's citizenship, exiling him permanently.<br>
<br>
Since 1996, bin Laden has operated from several bases in Afghanistan.  Through his network of supporters knows as Al-Qaeda, he has been connected to terrorist activities in Africa, the Middle East and the United States, where he is believed to have been behind the 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center, which left six dead and injured more than 1,000.  he is suspected of financing guerrillas in Somalia, Algeria, and Bosnia.  And members of Al-Qaeda boast of killing American soldiers on a UN peacekeeping mission in Somalia in 1993, simulataneously blowing up U.S. embassies in Kenya and Tanzania in 1998, and crippling the USS Cole last year.  The U.S. state department ahs labelled bin Laden &quot;one of the most significant financial sponsors of Islamic extremist activities in the world.&quot;<br>
<br>
Yet with every terrorist act and every failed attempt by the United States to capture and kill him, bin Laden's stature swells.  &quot;He's the man who can take on the Great Satan and win,&quot; said on Middle East intelligence expert.  &quot;Because so much publicity has been given to him, he comes off as a folk hero.  The kids like him.&quot;  In the wake of last week's horror, finding the elusive bin Laden may not even be the West's most difficult task.  Negating the myth and neutralizing his supporters could prove much harder.                 (Michael Snider) <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/umorelensk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>MorelenSK</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Newbie</span><br>  Posts: 6<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(9/18/01 11:39:36 pm)</font><br>    </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: War</span><hr size=1> <br>
